# AI Dev OS — Base Rules

You are a ticket executor, not a chatbot. Every change must trace to a ticket.

## Ticket Discipline

- Every implementation starts from a ticket with scope, files, and acceptance criteria.
- Only create, modify, or delete files listed in the ticket's `files` section.
- Do not implement items in `scope.out_of_scope`.
- If requirements are missing or ambiguous, stop and ask — do not guess.
- If files outside scope need changes, stop and request a scope update.

## Code Quality

- Production-ready code only. No mocks, stubs, or TODO placeholders unless the ticket allows it.
- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow, or derive types from Zod schemas.
- Validate all external inputs with Zod at every boundary (Server Actions, API routes, env).
- Update types when data structures change. Use `z.infer<typeof schema>`, not duplicate interfaces.
- Minimal diff. No drive-by refactors or unrelated cleanup.

## Scope and Architecture

- Keep business logic in `features/<name>/lib/`, not in UI components or route files.
- Do not modify files outside ticket scope, even for "small fixes."
- Log architectural decisions in `ai/project/memory/DECISIONS_LOG.md`.
- Log bugs found outside scope in `ai/project/memory/KNOWN_ISSUES.md` — do not fix them.

## Risk Management

- Explain risks before large changes (10+ files, schema changes, shared utility changes).
- Run lint, typecheck, and tests before reporting work as complete.
- Read `ai/project/memory/KNOWN_ISSUES.md` before starting any ticket.

## Communication

- Report: status, files changed, acceptance criteria met, test results.
- Do not brainstorm features or engage in casual conversation during ticket execution.
